analysis.raw_analysis:
1. TRANSFORMATION TYPE: output keeps same 21x21 size; objects are copied (tiled) from anchor positions into straight runs (along row/column or diagonal) — ratio 1:1.

2. PATTERN: find a “corner” object and its two neighboring arm objects; leave the corner in place and replicate each arm object repeatedly away from the corner along its axis (to edge), creating a line/chain of that color.

3. KEY CHANGES:
- Ex1: color 1 (corner) stays; color 2 (left) is tiled left along the row; color 4 (upper/right) is tiled outward (right/up) forming chains.
- Ex2: color 8 (corner) stays; color 3 (right) copied to the right repeatedly; color 2 (below) copied downward repeatedly.
- Ex3: color 5 (corner) stays; color 6 (upper-right) copied along the up-right direction; color 1 (lower-right) copied along the down-right direction.

=== INPUT-INPUT COMPARISONS ===
All inputs contain three distinct colored objects. One object sits at the vertex of an L (the "corner"); the other two lie on roughly perpendicular rays from it. Colors vary but object shapes are preserved.

=== OUTPUT-OUTPUT COMPARISONS ===
All outputs keep the corner object unchanged and preserve grid size. The two other colors are repeatedly copied (unchanged) along straight lines from the corner; copies extend to the image edge with the same spacing/shape.

=== INPUT-OUTPUT COMPARISONS ===
Transformation: identify corner object (ex1 color 1; ex2 color 8; ex3 color 5). For each other object, compute the vector from corner to that object and tile that object repeatedly along that vector (1:1 spacing) until the border, preserving color (ex1: 2 tiled left, 4 tiled outward; ex2: 3 → right, 2 → down; ex3: 6 and 1 tiled outward from 5).

Reference objects: The object at the L‑vertex (the corner) is preserved and serves as the anchor/origin and orients the two arms.

Grid pattern: For every example, each non‑corner object is tiled repeatedly outward along the straight line connecting it to the corner (row, column or diagonal) until the grid edge.

Objects: Priority: corner (anchor, not copied) then the two arm objects (preserve color/orientation and replicate along their arm).

=== GENERAL RULE ===
Step 1: IF a connected region (object) has color != 0 THEN treat it as a candidate object for analysis (do not change its color or shape yet).

Step 2: IF among the candidate objects there exists an object O (color = c_o, c_o != 0) that has two other distinct candidate objects A and B whose centers each lie on two distinct straight rays originating at O (the straight line from O to A and the straight line from O to B are straight rows, columns, or ±45° diagonals and are not collinear) THEN label O as the corner (anchor) and leave O exactly in place (preserve its color c_o and shape).

Step 3: IF a candidate object P (color = c_p, c_p != 0 and c_p != c_o) lies on a straight ray originating at the corner O (center of P is on the same row, column, or ±45° diagonal through O) THEN create copies of P with identical shape, orientation and color c_p repeatedly along that same ray in the direction away from O using the same step vector (spacing) as the vector from O to P, and place copies until the grid edge is reached.

Step 4: IF placing a copy from Step 3 would fall on a cell already occupied by the corner object O THEN do not overwrite those corner cells (skip those placements).

Step 5: IF placing a copy from Step 3 would encounter an existing non-background object that is not the corner and is not part of the same arm being tiled, THEN stop further tiling in that ray at the cell before the collision (do not overwrite other distinct objects).

Step 6: IF there are two arm objects (one on each ray from O) THEN apply Step 3 independently to each arm object (tile each arm along its ray until edge or until stopped by Step 4/5).

Step 7: IF a cell is not the corner and is not created by tiling an arm in Steps 3–6 THEN leave that cell’s color unchanged (preserve background 0 and any other untouched objects).
